oc:kn_13aadc63 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting units and values fall outside expected ranges" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never aggressively clamp values to the valid range. If no conversion factor brings a value within range, return the original value unchanged." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Clamping destroys information and can hide clinically significant outliers that represent real pathology or data issues requiring investigation" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_1c8a3f0a a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing the unit conversion strategy" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use range-based detection rather than relying on unit metadata columns, which are frequently missing, inconsistent, or incorrect in multi-source healthcare datasets." ;
    oc:hasRationale "In real-world multi-hospital data, unit metadata is unreliable (20-40% mixed units). Range-based inference is more robust." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_2909349c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting units for multi-unit features" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Some features have three possible unit representations (e.g., Magnesium: mg/dL, mmol/L, mEq/L). All conversion factors must be tried sequentially, not just the most common one." ;
    oc:hasRationale "8 features in the CKD lab panel have three possible units; trying only the primary conversion factor will miss values reported in the third unit system" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_3a39581d a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When validating converted values against reference ranges" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use a 5% tolerance when checking range boundaries after conversion. Floating point precision issues from format conversions may place values slightly outside the boundary (e.g., 0.49 instead of 0.50)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Numeric format transformations (especially European decimal → float) introduce small floating point errors that are artifacts, not actual out-of-range values" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_4d3d2a19 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before any unit conversion step" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Always parse numeric formats (scientific notation, European decimals, whitespace) BEFORE attempting unit conversion. Format issues will cause conversion failures." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scientific notation like 1.5e3 or European decimal commas will produce incorrect conversion results if not normalized first" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_9b2680e5 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Preprocessing step before any harmonization" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Filter out rows with ANY missing values before harmonization. Only complete records with all features measured can be reliably processed." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Incomplete records (partial lab panels, cancelled orders, data entry errors) produce unreliable harmonization results and can bias downstream analysis" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e55e00a9 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When detecting which values need unit conversion" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If a value falls outside the expected min/max range for its feature, it likely needs unit conversion. Try each conversion factor until one brings the value into range." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Range-based detection is more reliable than relying on unit metadata which is often missing or inconsistent in multi-source healthcare data" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_fbc8c295 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Final output formatting step" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Format all harmonized values to exactly 2 decimal places, which is standard precision for clinical lab results." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Clinical lab results are conventionally reported at 2 decimal precision; extra decimals are noise, fewer lose meaningful precision" ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

